@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

@{b}@{fg shine}Introduction - About FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

FlashPlayer is a player for Macromedia's (now Adobe's) "flash" interactive
animation format, also known as SWF. The flash format was originally
invented as a very bandwidth-efficient means for delivering animation
across the Internet. It has since grown into an interactive presentation
format, complete with its own scripting language.

Like most flash animation players for the Amiga, FlashPlayer is based on
the open-source @{"swf library" link "Credits" 23} by Olivier Debon. FlashPlayer has made many
improvements to the original swf library, and has integrated it into an
IBrowse plugin. However, despite the improvements, FlashPlayer still
suffers many of the limitations of the swf library, including limited or
missing support for many of the newer additions to the flash format.

This documentation is for the IBrowse plugin version of FlashPlayer. It
works with IBrowse 2.4 or later to allow flash animations to be viewed as
part of a web page. A standalone version of FlashPlayer is also available;
it is capable of playing flash animations without the need for IBrowse (or
any other program).

@{b}Features:@{ub}

o @{i}Fairly complete support for Flash 1 through Flash 3 formats @{ui}

  Most of these older animations will play pretty much as intended.

o @{i}Limited support for Flash 4 and up @{ui}

  Does not support scripting, so while it will not malfunction when
  presented with a newer animation, it may not play it as intended. Newer
  animations may play just fine, however, if they don't use any of the
  unsupported features (I've seen Flash 8 and Flash 9 animations that work
  fine with FlashPlayer).

o @{i}Fully integrated with IBrowse @{ui}

  Flash animations appear as part of the web page, and can interact with
  the browser as well as the user to load other animations, visit other
  pages, and even execute Javascript.

o @{i}Uses @{"render.library and guigfx.library" link "Credits" 80} for best image quality @{ui}

  Plugins don't have access to the IBrowse rendering engine so, like the
  standalone FlashPlayer, the plugin uses these two libraries for its
  graphics output. This allows it to fully support any screen mode that
  IBrowse itself supports, including OCS, ECS, AGA, CyberGraphics, and
  Picasso 96. Uses dithering for improved display quality on color-mapped
  screens.

o @{i}Uses @{"AHI" link "Credits" 86} for flexible audio output @{ui}

  Plays sound on any hardware for which AHI has a driver. Supports 16-bit
  audio.

o @{i}Built-in decoding of MP3 sounds @{ui}

  Contains an integrated version of the open-source @{"MAD MP3 decoder" link "Credits" 45}; does
  not require mpega.library or other external decoder.

o @{i}Support for alternate hardware platforms @{ui}

  Because it does not depend on native Amiga hardware for graphics or
  sound, the FlashPlayer plugin works with Amiga emulators and with the
  latest Amiga hardware.

o @{i}Configurable, for maximum flexibility @{ui}

  Uses @{"tooltypes" link "Configuration" 0} to configure its operation (set the playback quality,
  enable or disable sound, streaming sound, and looping, adjust the sound
  buffer size, and set the diagnostic output level).

o @{i}Selectable diagnostic output @{ui}

  Can be set to generate no diagnostic output, output only on errors, or
  to trace its operation, which can be helpful in understanding why a
  particular animation is not playing as expected. Diagnostic output
  appears in a separate console window.

@{b}Limitations:@{ub}

o @{i}Does not support many of the newer additions to the flash format @{ui}

  Chief among these is the scripting language first added to Flash 4, and
  extended in newer flash versions. Some animations depend on scripting and
  will not run without it, while others use it only as an enhancement, and
  can still be viewed to some extent even without scripting support.

o @{i}Limitations in the IBrowse plugin API @{ui}

  As one of the first plugins for IBrowse, the FlashPlayer plugin uncovered
  some @{"bugs and limitations in the IBrowse plugin interface" link "IB24Limitations" 0}. These will be
  addressed in future versions of IBrowse, but IBrowse 2.4 users will need
  to keep them in mind.

o @{i}Resource-intensive @{ui}

  While the flash files themselves can be small, decoding and presenting
  them requires lots of memory and lots of processor cycles (a reflection
  of the origins of the flash format and of the swf presentation engine on
  the PC platform). This is in addition to the cycles that IBrowse itself
  needs to download and present the rest of the web page. A fairly high-end
  system is required to make practical use of the plugin, and even a 68060
  is unable to play most animations at their intended speed (or to play
  streaming sound without dropouts).

o @{i}No printing @{ui}

  The IBrowse plugin interface does not currently support printing, so
  printing (via Postscript) a web page with a flash animation will result
  in blank space where the animation is supposed to be.

o @{i}No PowerPC version @{ui}

  There is no OS4/PPC version of the FlashPlayer plugin because I don't
  have a PPC system to develop it on. The @{"source code" link "Credits" 11} is available, if
  anyone wants to port it to the PPC.

@endnode

@node "Varieties" "Varieties of FlashPlayer"

@{b}@{fg shine}Varieties of FlashPlayer - The standalone player vs. the plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

Starting with version 1.5, there are two varieties of FlashPlayer- a
standalone player, and an IBrowse plugin. Each is available separately,
and each has its uses.

Most flash content is found on the web, and the most common way to view it
is with a web browser. This allows the animations to be integrated into the
web page in a manner that cannot easily be duplicated with a standalone
player. The IBrowse plugin version of FlashPlayer is obviously best suited
to this use.

However, the standalone version of FlashPlayer also has uses. There are
times when it may be desirable to view an animation without having the
overhead of a web browser present. The standalone player also allows more
control over the presentation of the animation than does the plugin.

It's also easy to set up an icon for a flash file to run the standalone
player when it is double-clicked, and the tooltypes in the icon can be
customized to present that particular animation optimally.

Of course, not everyone uses IBrowse as their web browser, and so may not
be able to use the FlashPlayer plugin. Voyager has a flash plugin of its
own, though it's not nearly as powerful as FlashPlayer. As far as I know,
AWeb has no flash plugin. Users of both of these browsers may still find
the standalone version of FlashPlayer useful to view online flash content.

And finally, it's simply easier for me to test new FlashPlayer features
using the standalone player, without needing to bring IBrowse into the
equation.

@endnode

@node "Credits" "Credits"

@{b}@{fg shine}Credits - Who is behind FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

The FlashPlayer plugin is freely distributable, open-source software,
copyright ® 2008 - 2011 by Mike Steed. It is distributed WITHOUT WARRANTY,
under the terms of the @{"GNU General Public License (GPL)" link "COPYING/main" 0}. See the license
for details.

As an open-source project, FlashPlayer depends on the work of many
programmers:

o The Amiga-specific, user interface, and IBrowse interface portions of the
  program were written by Mike Steed @{b}(72207.463@compuserve.com)@{ub}. Source
  code for FlashPlayer (both the standalone and plugin versions) is
  available on Aminet at @{b}www.aminet.net/gfx/show/FlashPlayerSrc.lha@{ub}.

o Help in developing the IBrowse plugin version of FlashPlayer was provided
  by the IBrowse developers, in particular Oliver Roberts. The sample flash
  plugin provided by the IBrowse team was helpful in figuring out the
  IBrowse plugin API. The Netscape plugin API documentation and reference
  code was also helpful, since the IBrowse plugin API is based on the
  NPAPI.

o The flash format file decoding and presentation engine and the low-level
  graphics rendering and sound mixing portions of the program are via the
  swf library by Olivier Debon. Source to the original version of this
  library (version 0.4.10) is available at @{b}www.swift-tools.net/Flash@{ub}. The
  original library has been modified for Amiga compatibility and enhanced
  to add new features and to fix bugs by Mike Steed. Source to the modified
  library (version 0.5.6) is available as part of the FlashPlayer source.

o Many of the improvements to the swf library made during the development
  of FlashPlayer have also been incorporated into the GplFlash project, the
  "official" continuation of Olivier Debon's original work. GplFlash is
  available at @{b}sourceforge.net/projects/gplflash@{ub}.

o The swf library uses the libjpeg JPEG encoder/decoder library version 6b
  by the Independent JPEG Group, to decode the JPEG images found in flash
  files. Source to this library is available at @{b}www.ijg.org@{ub}.

o The swf library uses the zlib compression/decompression library version
  1.2.3 by Jean-loup Gailly and Mark Adler, to decode the zlib-compressed
  images found in flash files, and to decode compressed flash files.
  Source to this library is available at @{b}www.zlib.net@{ub}.

o Mike Steed's enhanced version of the swf library uses the libmad MPEG
  audio decoder library version 0.15.1b by Underbit Technologies, Inc, to
  decode MP3 audio found in flash files. Source to this library may be
  found at @{b}www.underbit.com/products/mad@{ub}.

o The embedded font found in the swf library of FlashPlayer v. 1.6 and
  later is NimbusSanL-Regu, from the Ghostscript font collection. It was
  converted to swf format by font2swf from the swftools suite, and was
  further massaged to reduce the amount of space required to store it.
  Source data for the processed font is part of the FlashPlayer source.

o FlashPlayer was inspired by the port of the swf library to the Amiga done
  by Paul Hill, and the player he wrote to utilize it (SwfPlayer version
  1.1). Both were formerly available at @{b}www.lagernet.clara.co.uk/@{ub}
  @{b}swfplayer.html@{ub}, but that site now seems to be offline. A bit of code
  from Paul's version made it into FlashPlayer as well.

o Further inspiration, testing under OS4, and collaboration on adding new
  feaures to the swf library came from Alexandre Balaban and his SwfPlayer
  version 1.2 and above, available on Aminet and at
  @{b}http://abalaban.free.fr/swfplayer.html@{ub}. Alexandre is also administrator
  of the GplFlash project.

o Beta testing and many example swf files were provided by Todd Oberly, who
  has an invaluable knack for finding files that make FlashPlayer fail in
  interesting ways. Many of the bug fixes were inspired by problems he
  found.

o Maxim Ilyin and Alex Ivanov ported the standalone FlashPlayer to MorphOS
  (available on Aminet), and also contributed the code to load Flash EXE
  files.

As an Amiga program, FlashPlayer depends on a number of third-party shared
libraries for its operation:

o guigfx.library and render.library by Timm S. M³ller / neoscientists are
  used to render the 24-bit output of the swf library's presentation engine
  to an Amiga screen. These libraries are included with FlashPlayer, and
  are also available on Aminet and at @{b}http://users.neoscientists.org/@{ub}
  @{b}~bifat/binarydistillery@{ub}.

o AHI by Martin Blom is used to play sounds generated by the swf library
  via either the Amiga's built-in audio output, or via a sound card. AHI is
  included with OS 3.5 and 3.9, and is also available on Aminet and at
  @{b}www.lysator.liu.se/ahi@{ub}.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

@{b}@{fg shine}Requirements - What is required to run the FlashPlayer plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

Since the FlashPlayer plugin runs as a part of IBrowse, the plugin's OS,
memory, and processor requirements start with those of IBrowse, the MUI
environment IBrowse runs in, and the TCP/IP stack it needs to fetch the web
pages. To this is added the memory and processor power required to decode
and display the flash files, which can be substantial.

Like IBrowse, the FlashPlayer plugin requires a 68020 or better processor.
(The plugin is compiled for a 68040, but will run on any processor from the
68020 through the 68060.) The plugin needs as much processor power as it
can get, so a 68040 or better processor is best. For speed, the plugin
requires that a hardware FPU (either built-in or external) be present.

As with IBrowse, the FlashPlayer plugin requires version 3.0 or better of
the Amiga OS. The plugin will work with any graphics system that IBrowse
itself supports. While not required, a graphics card (preferably Zorro 3
or local bus) is helpful, as it allows high-color animations to display
properly and at a decent speed.

Flash animations, especially those with sound, can require quite a bit of
memory- five to 10 MB above what IBrowse needs is a good idea, and even
more is better.

@endnode

@node "History" "Version History"

@{b}@{fg shine}Version History - The evolution of the FlashPlayer plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}Version 1.61 25-Feb-11 (posted to Aminet 26-Feb-11)@{ub}

This is an interim release of the plugin, which corrects a bug that caused
the plugin to crash with a small number of files when run under OS4. There
is no corresponding release of the standalone version of FlashPlayer, as it
did not suffer from the bug.

Bugs fixed:

o IBrowse passes flash files being downloaded to the plugin in chunks. The
  swf library used by the plugin could read from unallocated memory if the
  size of the flash animation was such that the last few bytes of the file
  appeared by themselves in one of these chunks. This was harmless under
  OS3, but caused a DSI crash under OS4.

o The plugin was inadvertently compiled without optimization for v. 1.6.
  This had little impact on speed, as the bulk of the work is done by the
  swf library, which was optimized. But might as well get it right this
  time.


@{b}Version 1.6 12-Oct-09 (posted to Aminet 30-Oct-09)@{ub}

I started to look at adding Flash 4 scripting to FlashPlayer, but realized
that a few features were still missing that would be necessary to support
scripting. Since these features were also useful without scripting, I went
ahead and added them to this version, instead of having to wait longer for
a version that includes scripting. Along the way I also tackled some long-
standing bugs.

Features added:

o Added partial support for edit text fields. Actual editing of text
  requires scripting, and so is not supported. However, edit text fields
  are often used to hold static ("read-only") text, and this text will be
  displayed.

  There are a number of limitations to the display of edit text. HTML-
  encoded text is displayed as plain text, with the HTML formatting
  removed. Scrolling of text is not supported, so text that is too large
  to fit will be clipped. Scripts may change the contents of an edit text
  field under script control; with no support for scripting, FlashPlayer
  cannot display this dynamic text.

  Despite these limitations, the ability to display edit text fields allows
  quite a bit of text that was formerly invisible to be seen, even though
  it may not look exactly as intended.

o Added partial support for device fonts, which are frequently used with
  edit text fields. Device fonts use platform-native fonts to display text,
  instead of swf fonts that are built into the animation. It would be diff-
  icult to support device fonts in a platform-independent fashion, so the
  swf library that FlashPlayer uses substitutes a built-in swf font in
  place of the platform-native font.

  To keep the size of the plugin down, there is only a single built-in
  font, which is used regardless of which device font the animation is
  requesting. Most animations that use device fonts request some variety of
  sans-serif font such as Arial or Helvetica, so for best compatibility the
  built-in font is a sans-serif font.

o The new JPEG image type added to Flash 10 files will be displayed, though
  without the deblocking filter associated with the image.

Improvements made:

o Button handling has been improved. FlashPlayer now recognizes the
  difference between menu buttons and push buttons, as defined by the Flash
  file format specification (previously all buttons were treated as menu
  buttons).

  Push buttons "capture" the mouse, so the button will remain active if the
  mouse is moved off of the button while held down. Any actions triggered
  by this activity will occur, rather than being ignored.

  If a button release sound is present it will be played; previously it was
  ignored. Some buttons that have an action associated with the release of
  the button will now have that action performed at the proper time;
  previously the action occurred when the button was pressed, instead.

o The swf library now recognizes all actions and tags found in Flash files
  up through version 10. Of course, it still doesn't understand most of the
  newer ones, but it will list them when an animation is loaded with the
  output set to verbose. Actions and tags that are unsupported by Flash-
  Player are listed as such.

o Enhanced the amount of information output when loading an animation if
  the output is set to verbose. In particular, a lot more information about
  scripts is generated. This is mainly for my benefit when doing develop-
  ment work on the library, but might be interesting to curious users as
  well.

o The plugin now spoofs as version 10 of the Adobe plugin.

o Some other enhancements were made to swf library features that aren't
  used by the plugin.

o The new v. 7 of the JPEG decoder library used by the swf library was
  tested, but it's both larger and slower than v. 6b, while not offering
  any new features that are useful to FlashPlayer. So FlashPlayer continues
  to use the older version.

Bugs fixed:

o Parsing of "dangerous" actions such as script branches was not aborted
  properly when the actions were attached to a button, sometimes causing
  other actions attached to the button to not be executed properly, even
  if they weren't "dangerous".

o Some other bugs were fixed in swf library features that aren't used by
  the plugin.


@{b}Version 1.5 26-Dec-08 (posted to Aminet 30-Dec-08)@{ub}

Version 1.5 of the FlashPlayer plugin is actually the first; it's numbered
1.5 to correspond to version 1.5 of the standalone FlashPlayer.

The swf library used to decode and process the flash files in the plugin
is identical to that in the equivalent version of the standalone player.
Compared to v. 1.4 of the standalone player, the plugin makes the following
changes and improvements to the swf library.

Features added:

o Now that Adobe has made the Flash 9 specification freely available, at
  least partial support for some of the new Flash 8 and Flash 9 features
  has been added.

  The new high-resolution font format added to Flash 8 is now supported,
  though FlashPlayer doesn't contain the new high-quality font rendering
  engine, and so displays these fonts at the same resolution and quality
  as the older ones.

  FlashPlayer will also draw the new shapes and morphing shapes added to
  Flash 8. For speed reasons it does not support most of the new features
  of those shapes (such as run-time filter effects, focal gradients, and
  selectable line cap and join styles), so while the shapes will appear,
  they might not look like entirely like they were intended to.

  The swf library now recognizes all actions and tags found in Flash files
  up through version 9. Of course, it still doesn't understand many of the
  newer ones, but it will list them when an animation is loaded with the
  output set to verbose. Actions and tags that are unsupported by Flash-
  Player are listed as such.

  FlashPlayer still sometimes reports unknown tags. These are either pro-
  prietary tags inserted by flash authoring tools, or tags that are un-
  documented by Adobe.

Improvements made:

o Optimized the swf library used by FlashPlayer to mix colors more
  efficiently when rendering an animation, leading to a significant
  speedup.

o Diagnostic output is now written using Amiga library routines, rather
  than the compiler's file writing routines. This removes a couple of
  Kbytes of code, making FlashPlayer a little smaller.

o The term "(unsupported)" is used a lot in the diagnostic output. The
  code has been optimized so that the term is only stored once, and that
  single instance is used by all of the diagnostic output. This reduces
  the size of the plugin by another 1.5 Kbytes.

o Animations with only a single frame no longer loop, even if looping is
  enabled. These animations typically use sprites embedded within the
  single frame for their action, and looping prevented the sprites from
  running. This reduces the number of animations that don't play correctly
  when looping is enabled, and has allowed looping to be enabled rather
  than disabled by default.

Bugs fixed:

o Fixed bugs in the swf library that caused the rightmost column and bottom
  line of the animation to not be drawn. This was difficult to see in the
  standalone player due to the proximity of the missing lines to the window
  borders, but was quite apparent in the plugin.

o The swf library would crash when loading a broken animation that had more
  frames than it declared it had. The library will now ignore any frames
  beyond the number declared.

o The swf library would crash or cause Enforcer hits when trying to render
  very long lines, such as a shape that's been magnified until only a
  small portion of it is visible. Clipping is now performed to prevent
  this.

o The improved color reduction that was added to FlashPlayer v. 1.4 when
  processing lossless-compressed bitmap images did not correctly handle
  24-bit images without an alpha channel, displaying random garbage instead
  of the image. It now handles these images correctly.

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Installation - How to install the FlashPlayer plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

Installation of the FlashPlayer plugin is fairly simple, so no install
script is provided. Start by dragging the plugin (called npflashplayer.lib-
rary) into the Plugins drawer inside the drawer where IBrowse is installed.
IBrowse will only work with one plugin of a given type, so if you've got
the demo IBrowse flash plugin (called npflash.library) installed, you'll
need to remove it. If you've already got the proper version of guigfx.lib-
rary and render.library installed, that's it- you're done.

If you don't have these two libraries installed, you'll need to install the
appropriate version for your processor. The libraries can be installed
either into the Plugins drawer where the plugin was placed, or into LIBS:.

 CPU    guigfx.library        render.library
 -----  --------------------  --------------------
 68020  guigfx.library_FPU    render.library
 68030  guigfx.library_FPU    render.library
 68040  guigfx.library_68040  render.library_68040
 68060  guigfx.library_68060  render.library_68060

Whichever version of the libraries you choose, they must be renamed to
simply @{i}guigfx.library@{ui} and @{i}render.library@{ui}.

FlashPlayer does not require any special configuration of AHI; if you've
already got it installed, FlashPlayer will use it. Note that FlashPlayer
depends on AHI to mix together the audio streams from all the flash anim-
ations that may be running, so make sure you configure AHI to have enough
audio channels. FlashPlayer will run without AHI, it just won't be able to
play sounds.

@endnode

@node "IB24Limitations" "Limitations of IBrowse 2.4"

@{b}@{fg shine}Limitations of IBrowse 2.4@{ub}@{fg text}

Because the FlashPlayer plugin was one of the first to be written for
IBrowse, it uncovered some bugs and limitations in the IBrowse plugin
interface. The IBrowse programmers are aware of these, and will be add-
ressing them in a future version of IBrowse. Until then, users of the
FlashPlayer plugin with IBrowse 2.4 will need to keep them in mind.

o Because of its use of @{"render.library and guigfx.library" link "Credits" 80}, the FlashPlayer
  plugin accesses the IBrowse display differently than the demo flash
  player plugin that the IBrowse team used for testing. This uncovered an
  issue with the way IBrowse sometimes closes its display without letting
  the plugin know.

  As a result, the FlashPlayer plugin will crash (which in turn crashes
  IBrowse) if the IBrowse display is closed and then reopened while a flash
  animation is running (even if it is not visible). The two likely causes
  of this are iconifying and then restoring IBrowse, and changing the
  IBrowse preferences. The workaround is to be sure no flash animations are
  running when doing either of these things.

o Due to a bug, IBrowse never closes a flash file that it has loaded at the
  request of another flash animation. This leads to a memory leak, as the
  unclosed file will remain in memory, even when the offending animation is
  no longer being viewed. The memory will eventually be freed, when IBrowse
  is quit. There is no problem with flash files loaded by a web page, which
  is the more common scenario.

o IBrowse ignores "javascript:" URLs sent to it by a plugin, instead of
  executing the attached Javascript as it is supposed to. This can prevent
  the flash animation from being able to interact with the browser as
  intended.

o Plugins are currently always active, even if they are not visible. This
  means that they continue to consume processor power, and continue to play
  sound. Sometimes this may be desirable, but sometimes it is not. Future
  versions of IBrowse will allow plugins to become inactive under some
  conditions, much like it currently does with GIF animations.

@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"

@{b}@{fg shine}Configuration - How to configure the FlashPlayer plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

The FlashPlayer plugin is configured by means of tooltypes stored in its
icon. Some of the tooltypes are used by IBrowse to tell it about the
plugin; others are used to specify the operation of the plugin. In either
case the option's keyword is given, followed (with no spaces) by an
equals sign, followed (again, no spaces) by the option's setting (for
example, SOUND=NO). Although the keywords and options are shown in upper
case, they are in fact not case sensitive.

o @{b}NAME=<Plugin Name>@{ub}
  This tooltype is used by IBrowse, and is ignored by the plugin. It
  specifies the name by which the plugin is known to the browser, and to
  any web site that inquires as to which plugins the browser has available.
  The default name is "Shockwave Flash", and because many web sites will
  only recognize a flash player by this name, it should not be changed.

o @{b}DESCRIPTION=<Plugin Description>@{ub}
  This tooltype is used by IBrowse, and is ignored by the plugin. It pro-
  vides a description by which the plugin is known to the browser, and to
  any web site that inquires as to which plugins the browser has available.
  The default name is "Shockwave Flash 10.0 r32", which spoofs the identity
  of the current Adobe flash plugin (yes, plugins have to spoof, too).

  Because many web sites use this description to determine if a flash
  plugin is present and which version of flash it supports, it should not
  be changed. This description is displayed by IBrowse when the "About
  plugins" menu item is selected.

o @{b}AUTHOR=<Author's Name>@{ub}
o @{b}COPYRIGHT=<Copyright Info>@{ub}
  These tooltypes are used by IBrowse, and are ignored by the plugin. This
  information is displayed by IBrowse when the "About plugins" menu item is
  selected, but otherwise serves no purpose.

o @{b}MIMETYPE=<MIME Type and File Type>@{ub}
  This tooltype is used by IBrowse, and is ignored by the plugin. It tells
  the browser which MIME types (and their associated file types) this
  plugin supports. These are determined by the construction of the plugin,
  and should not be changed. This information is displayed by IBrowse when
  the "About plugins" menu item is selected.

o @{b}QUALITY <LOW or MEDIUM or HIGH>@{ub}
  This tooltype specifies the presentation quality to be used for playing
  the animation. In general, the higher the presentation quality, the
  slower the animation will play, and the more memory it will use. Only the
  first letter of the quality setting is read, so LOW may be abbreviated as
  LO or L; the same applies to the other settings.

  Adjusting the quality currently has the following effect:

  LOW quality uses no dithering on colormapped screens (no effect on high-
      or true-color graphics card screens), and plays mono sounds at
      11 KHz.

  MEDIUM quality uses EDD dithering on colormapped screens (no effect on
      high- or true-color graphics card screens), and plays stereo sounds
      at 11 KHz.

  HIGH quality uses Floyd-Steinberg dithering on colormapped screens (no
      effect on high- or true-color graphics card screens), and plays
      stereo sounds at 22 KHz.

  The default is MEDIUM quality.

o @{b}SOUND <YES or XSTREAM or NO>@{ub}
  This tooltype enables (YES) or disables (NO) the playing of sounds con-
  tained within an animation. Because FlashPlayer usually can't play
  streaming sound fast enough to avoid dropouts (especially when the
  browser is also active), XSTREAM may be used to disable only streaming
  sound, while enabling all other sound. Only the first letter of the
  setting is read, so YES may be abbreviated as Y, XSTREAM may be
  abbreviated as X, and NO may be abbreviated as N.

  Disabling streaming sound can save quite a bit of memory, as there is no
  need to store the streaming sound data in memory. Disabling sound
  completely saves even more memory, by eliminating the need for sound
  buffers, and the need to load AHI.

  The default setting is YES unless AHI cannot be opened, in which case
  sound will be disabled.

o @{b}SOUNDBUF <KBytes>@{ub}
  This tooltype sets the size of the sound buffers used by the plugin, in
  kbytes. The default if not otherwise set (or if set to zero) is 96 kB.
  The maximum is 255 kB. FlashPlayer uses double-buffering for improved
  sound quality, so there will be two buffers of this size allocated. The
  size of the buffers is automatically doubled when playing at HIGH
  quality, to accommodate the faster sample rate, and is automatically
  halved when playing at LOW quality, because mono sound requires fewer
  samples.

  Note that each flash object being displayed by the browser gets its own
  set of sound buffers, so the total amount of memory devoted to sound
  buffers can be significant. Making the buffers smaller reduces memory
  usage, and allows more responsive sound (that is, the sound is better
  synchronized to an action, such as a button press, that triggered it).
  However, small buffers are also more prone to dropouts as the frame rate
  of the animation slows due to a large or complex animation, or to other
  browser activity.

  The default buffer size of 96 kB is a reasonable compromise for most
  systems and most animations, but for best sound reproduction you may wish
  to experiment to determine the optimum buffer size for your system.
  Generally, the best size for the buffer is the smallest that avoids
  dropouts.

o @{b}LOOP <YES or NO>@{ub}
  This tooltype enables (YES) or disables (NO) automatic looping of anim-
  ations when they reach their end. Only the first letter of the yes/no
  setting is read, so YES may be abbreviated as Y and NO may be abbreviated
  as N.

  The default is for looping to be enabled.

o @{b}OUTPUT <NORMAL or QUIET or VERBOSE>@{ub}
  This tooltype sets the level of diagnostic output presented by the plugin
  as it runs. Only the first letter of the diagnostic setting is read, so
  NORMAL may be abbreviated as NORM or N; the same applies to the other
  settings.

  When QUIET is specified, the plugin will generate no diagnostic output,
  even when an error occurs. When NORMAL is specified, only errors are
  output.

  When VERBOSE is specified, the plugin outputs various information (and
  quite a lot of it) on the file decoding and presentation process, as well
  as errors. Displaying all this information can make loading an animation
  rather slow. There's no way to turn verbose output off once it's started,
  but the display can be sped up by making the diagnostic window small, or
  even hiding it behind another window.

@endnode

@node "Operation" "Operation"

@{b}@{fg shine}Operation - How to use the FlashPlayer plugin@{ub}@{fg text}

@{b}Plugin Activation@{ub}

IBrowse will automatically load the FlashPlayer plugin when it encounters a
flash animation on a web page, and will automatically stream the flash file
to the plugin to be displayed. If there is more than one flash animation on
the page, additional instances of the plugin will be created to display
them. There is no limit to the number of animations that may be displayed,
except for memory and the user's tolerance of the speed decrease due to
having many animations playing at the same time.

When no flash files are loaded, the plugin frees its resources (sound
buffers, etc.) in order to minimize memory usage. The plugin will normally
remain in RAM even when no longer in use, for faster activation the next
time it is needed. But should memory run low, an inactive plugin will be
unloaded in order to free up some memory.

@{b}Plugin Display@{ub}

A flash animation is able to ask IBrowse to load another animation to be
played within the current one ("picture in picture" mode). An animation may
also direct IBrowse to a different web page, just like a regular page link.
Note that the plugin is not able to display the target of a link when the
mouse passes over it, because links in a flash animation may be interact-
ive, and may go to different targets depending on the current state of
the animation. This state can't be determined until the button is actually
clicked, so the plugin doesn't know which target (if any) to display.

In IBrowse 2.4 plugins are always active, and so any loaded flash anim-
ation will play continuously, even if it is not visible. Future versions of
IBrowse will allow plugins to become inactive under certain conditions,
much like it does currently with GIF animations.

Flash animations will play at whatever size the web page containing them
specifies. This is almost always the native size of the animation. However,
if you ask IBrowse to load just the flash file (from the cache browser, for
instance), or if you select "View separately" from the plugin FAB menu,
the animation will be scaled to the full size of the browser window or tab.
This is consistent with the way plugins work on other platforms, and may be
used as a handy way to enlarge or reduce an animation.

@{b}Plugin Information@{ub}

When the mouse pointer is moved over a flash animation, the IBrowse status
line will display information about the animation, taking the place of the
standalone player's "Movie Info" requester. From left to right, the flash
version of the animation is given, then the name of the file, then in par-
entheses the intended frame rate of the animation, the number of frames,
and the native size of the animation in pixels. IBrowse may trim some of
this information if it's too long to fit on the status line.

@{b}Plugin Control@{ub}

When the mouse passes over a button or user control on the animation, the
pointer changes to the standard IBrowse "pointing hand", to signal that
clicking the mouse will perform some action (but note that because Flash-
Player doesn't currently support flash scripting, clicking the mouse may
sometimes have no effect, even when the pointing hand is present).

IBrowse doesn't currently allow plugins to have their own menus, so it is
not possible to stop, single step, or rewind the animation as it is with
the standalone version of FlashPlayer. Nor can you change any of the plugin
@{"configuration options" link "Configuration" 0} while the plugin is running. A future version of
IBrowse may allow plugins to add their own items to the plugin FAB menu,
overcoming this limitation.

Neither does IBrowse currently allow plugins to capture the keyboard, so
it is not possible for the plugin to accept keyboard commands the way the
standalone version of FlashPlayer does.

@{b}Diagnostic Output Window@{ub}

When the FlashPlayer plugin generates diagnostic output, it does so to a
console window, which always opens on the Workbench screen. All active
plugins use the same console window, which can result in a confusing
display if more than one plugin is generating diagnostic output at the
same time.

The console window opens only when needed, so it will not open if there is
no output to display, even if diagnostic output has been enabled. The
window may be closed using its close box at any time, even while the plugin
is active; if need be, another window will be opened for displaying further
output. The window will automatically be closed when the last active plugin
is closed.

@endnode

@node "Miscellany" "Miscellany"

@{b}@{fg shine}Miscellany - Odds and ends regarding FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

As I did not write the code that provides the bulk of FlashPlayer's
functionality, I cannot speak much as to its robustness. The jpeg, zlib,
and MAD libraries are well used, even in the PC/Unix world, and so are
presumably pretty solid. The swf library is less well used, as Adobe
supplies flash players for most platforms. In my testing the swf library
has proven to be solid when playing valid swf files. It may not be able to
properly present everything in the file, but it doesn't crash or otherwise
misbehave. I have not attempted to test it with improperly formatted files
to see how it handles these, nor have I tested it under low memory
conditions.

I have only a single system on which to develop and test FlashPlayer (an
Amiga 3000 desktop with a Cyberstorm MkIII 50 MHz 68060 and 32 + 14 + 2 MB
of RAM, running OS 3.9 or OS 3.1, with a Picasso II running Picasso 96, and
native Amiga sound running AHI 6). The use of libraries such as guigfx and
AHI to handle graphical and sound output should minimize the possibility of
problems on other systems, but something still could go wrong.

---

If FlashPlayer doesn't seem to be playing an animation properly, it
probably isn't. As mentioned elsewhere, the swf library that FlashPlayer
uses @{"does not support all flash features" link "Introduction" 82}, even in animations that don't use
scripting. Similar to the way Amiga web browsers compare with their PC
brethren, FlashPlayer works well enough to give you the gist of most
animations that don't require advanced features, but they will often look
or sound different than when they're played on a PC using Adobe's flash
player.

---

In testing the FlashPlayer plugin, I have observed some cases where flash
animations are not displayed, even though the plugin is present. (Sometimes
the animation is simply missing, while other times you get a still image,
or even a "you need to install the flash player" message.) Sometimes this
is due to overly fussy flash plugin detection code used by the web page,
which does not recognize FlashPlayer, despite its attempts to spoof as the
official Adobe player.

In other cases style sheets (CSS) are used to layer a flash animation on
top of a still image that is intended to be seen if no flash plugin is
present. Because IBrowse does not currently support CSS, it cannot display
the animation, leaving only the still image visible.

Most flash detection code is Javascript, so disabling Javascript will
prevent many flash animations from displaying. And setting IBrowse to spoof
as Internet Explorer in order to access a particular web site may also
prevent flash animations from playing, as IE uses ActiveX rather than
plugins to to display flash files.

@endnode

@node "Future" "The Future"

@{b}@{fg shine}The Future - What's ahead for FlashPlayer@{ub}@{fg text}

My plan had been that FlashPlayer 1.4 would be the last 1.x version, and
that the next release would be v. 2.0. I planned to make the standalone
version of FlashPlayer into a "shell" that used the new plugin to do most
of the work. That way, I wouldn't need to duplicate the swf library into
both the plugin and the standalone. But the IBrowse plugin interface turned
out to use MUI in a way that would have been difficult to duplicate for a
non-MUI application. So instead, I have continued on the 1.x path, and the
plugin and the standalone player will continue to be separate projects.

I have a full-time job and family commitments, and so don't have a lot of
time to devote to projects such as FlashPlayer. Because of this, it tends
to be quite a while between updates to the program (historically, almost a
year). Still, I hope to keep playing with the @{"swf library" link "Credits" 23}, fixing
shortcomings and adding new features to better enable it to present flash
animations. I'll also update the plugin as future versions of IBrowse add
support for features like plugin menus and printing.

Beyond that lies the realm of more extensive changes to the swf library.
The most called-for change would be the addition of scripting support, to
handle the large number of animations that rely on this. The handling of
Flash 4 scripting seems feasible- I intend to look into the possibility of
adding it to a future version of FlashPlayer, but make no promises. Flash 5
scripting is much more complicated, and it seems unlikely at this point
that it will ever become a part of FlashPlayer. The script format has
changed again as of Flash 9, so a full-featured player now needs to support
three scripting languages- even more unlikely for FlashPlayer.

Naturally, as an open-source project, the code to FlashPlayer is available
to anyone who wants to enhance it or extend it in new directions, just as I
have done with the original swf library.

@{b}Gnash@{ub}

Gnash @{b}(www.gnash.org)@{ub} is the most popular and most advanced of the open
source flash players. Among other things, it supports most of the Flash 5
script language (and is making progress on the Flash 9 version), and it can
play streaming video from web sites like YouTube. I'm sometimes asked if it
makes sense to continue to develop FlashPlayer, rather than working towards
porting Gnash to the Amiga.

The problem with porting Gnash is that it depends on a bunch of other
libraries for many of its features, and few of them are available for the
Amiga. So in order to port Gnash itself, I'd have to first port all these
other libraries (which may in turn depend on yet other libraries), making
it into a very large project.

Gnash is also being developed on GHz-class PCs, and so is oriented more
towards capability and reduced development time than efficiency. As such,
its performance would be poor on the Amiga platform, particularly on 68K
Amigas.

So while it would be nice to have the capabilities of Gnash available on
the Amiga, it isn't currently practical. But while I can't just port Gnash
to the Amiga, I can always borrow some code - and some knowledge - from it.

@endnode
